1 Introduction

The following document includes the descriptive Bayesian meta-analysis that you desired to have for this meta-analysis project.

As I have indicated earlier and ran multiple rounds of analyses using the programs that I specifically developed during the course of this project, for this type of data, regression-based models can better take care of longitudinal data. But those models donât produce descriptive results which you desired to achieve.

The following include both tables and results. Pick based on your preference. These results are the final one which we agreed in August 2020 and I implemented all of them via programming.

The 15 refined and agreed upon moderators include:

  • profic: replace 77s with 99s
  • cf.type: replace 15s with 99s
  • Length: replace 0s with 1s and replace 3s with 2s (to end up with three categories: 1 & 2 & 99)
  • graded: replace 88s with 99s

3 The methodology section

  • We calculated a within-group Cohenâs d effect size for each group in a controlled study using the exact pre-post correlation from the study (e.g., when paired t-test was reported), by imputation (i.e., using pre-post correlation from another group in the same study), or assuming a medium-high correlation (r = .5) for the missing correlation (see Boresntiein et al, 2009). Then, we calculated a dint effect size along with its standard error (see Viechtbauer, 2007) for each dint. We included all complex-structure WCF studies including multi-outcome, multi-group, and multiple-posttest studies. This stage led to 514 within-group Cohenâs d effect sizes, and 257 dints. Adopting an open-science approach, our full dataset for this study is publicly available HERE (this is another new, updated shortened dataset for this publication only).

  • 20 of the total 52 studies contained one or more negative effect sizes before averaging. After correlated averaging (we used r = .5 as the common correlation bet. Effect sizes), 8 average effect sizes from 8 studies (i.e., Bitc_Yng_Cmrn; Diab_b; Eki_diGnro; Fazio; Jhowry; Trscott_Hsu; VanBe_Jng_Ken; Zhang) became negative. See the Outlier control and publication bias section for a discussion of how outlying effect sizes were treated.

  • The model of our meta-analysis study is Bayesian random-effects designed to estimates 2 parameters which are diagrammatically shown in the following Figure:



  • In the above figure, parameter 1 is the mean (\(\mu\)) or overall effect size, and parameter 2 is Tau (\(\tau\)) or standard deviation of the distribution of the study effect sizes.

  • In the following tables, Mu denotes the posterior mean for the mean effect in a Bayesian random-effects meta-analysis conducted in each row of the table.

  • In the following tables, Low and Up denote the 95% Bayesian high-density credible intervals for the posterior mean effect. They give us an indication of the 95% most credible effect sizes had we collected the entire population of WCF studies ever conducted.

  • In the following tables, Perc.mu denotes the percentage interpretation of the mean effect in each row of the table. Any percentage larger than 0% shows an improvement for treatment groups over control groups in the WCF literature in each row of the table

  • In the following tables, K denotes the number of studies. However, because a single study could possess group-level features (e.g., some groups receiving oral feedback, but not others), it may be counted multiply in the K column. Therefore, the K column total could be larger than 50, the total number of studies, for group-level moderators. For study-level moderators (e.g., proficiency), K column total always equals 50.

  • In the following tables, BF01.mu denotes a Bayes Factor (see Norouzian et al, 2019). It tells us if the mean effect in each row of the table could provide evidence in favor of the null hypothesis that mean effect = 0. The smaller the value, the larger the evidence against the null hypothesis (and in favor of the alternative hypothesis i.e., mean effect \(\neq\) 0).

  • In the following tables, BF01.tau denotes a Bayes Factor (see Norouzian et al, 2019). It tells us if the heterogeneity between studiesâ mean effects (Tau) in each row of the table could provide evidence in favor of the null hypothesis that heterogeneity = 0. The smaller the value, the larger the evidence against the null hypothesis (and in favor of the alternative hypothesis i.e., heterogeneity \(\neq\) 0).

  • Closely related to tau (heterogeneity in effect sizes in sd unit), is I2 (Higgins and Thompson 2002; Higgins, Thompson, Deeks, & Altman, 2003). I2 denotes the percentage of the total variability in a set of effect sizes due to between-study heterogeneity. Higgins and Thompson (2002) proposed a tentative classification of I2 values where percentages of around 25% (I2 = 25), 50% (I2 = 50), and 75% (I2 = 75) would denote low, medium, and high heterogeneity, respectively.

5 Outlier control and publication bias

From our initial 52 studies, two studies (Al_Ajmi and Seiff_ElSak) were excluded because (a) they included extremely large effect sizes (e.g., 5.09) that had extreme effect on the overall effect, (b) a close inspection of the studiesâ treatments, setting, operational definitions and procedures did not suggest any notable difference to justify such drastically large effects relative to other studies in the WCF literature and (c) they made the funnel plot of the study effect sizes extremely asymmetric causing the eggerâs test of funnel plot symmetry to become highly significant (p < .001).

Eggerâs Test Before Outliers Removal
b1 z.value p.value b1.lower b1.upper result
4.8173 4.3203 0 2.6319 7.0027 ***

For the sake of transparency, our dataset before the treatment of outlying effect sizes is publicly available HERE and our dataset after the treatment of outlying effect sizes is also publicly available HERE.

5.1 Eggerâs Test for publication bias

After the treatment of the outlying effect sizes as described in the previous section, we conducted an eggerâs test of funnel plot symmetry. Given that the p-value was larger than .05, we concluded that our funnel plot is symmetric and no major publication bias issues in the collected sample of studies exist under the common assumptions for publication bias (Boresntiein et al, 2009, Chapter 30).

Eggerâs Test After Outliers Removal
b1 z.value p.value b1.lower b1.upper result
1.5889 1.4949 0.1349 -0.4942 3.672 :-))

In the funnel plot further below, gray points are shrinkage estimates i.e., less precise outliers are (those with larger SE) shrunk more toward the mean effect via random-effects model and Bayesian shrinkage i.e., use of a prior on the mean effect size to blunt extreme effect sizes from studies.

5.2 Trim and Fill Method

We also assessed the risk of pubication bias via a third method known as Trim and Fill (Duval, 2005; Duval & Tweedie, 2000). In this non-parameteric method, the goal is to impute (i.e., fill) the possible effect sizes missing, due to a particular selection mechanism, from the literature to achieve a more symmetric funnel plot of effect sizes on either side of the plot.

As shown in the follwing figure, in our case, the Trim and Fill method suggested that no fill-studies to either side of the plot are needed to achieve a more symteric view of the WCF literature. Therefore, these results concur with with the previous eggerâs test result as regards the issue of publication bias.

5.3 Vevea and Hedges Method

Finally, we used a fourth confirmatory method to detect publication bias. Vevea and Hedges (1995) proposed a method where the original meta-analysis and a bias-adjusted meta-analysis using weights associated with the effect sizesâ p-values are compared to one another (see Vevea & Hedges 1995 and Vevea & Woods, 2005 for details).

Once both the unadjusted and adjusted meta-analytic models are obtained, a likelihood-ratio test compares the two models. If the likelihood-ratio test is significant, it means that the biased-adjusted model better fits the study effect sizes, and hence the presence of publication bias. Otherwise, the risk of publicatio bias is minimal.

Vevea & Hedge Method for Publication Bias
Df X^2 p.value
Likelihood Ratio Test: 1 0.2335 0.6289

Overall, our visual (funnel plot), and statistical methods (Eggerâs test, Trim and Fill method, and Vevea and Hedges Method) suggested no major problem with respect to publication bias.
